	"class": "vulnerability",
	"metadata": {
		"title": "kernel: KVM: nVMX: missing IBPB when exiting from nested guest can lead to Spectre v2 attacks (moderate)",
		"reference": [
			{
				"ref_id": "CVE-2022-2196",
				"ref_url": "https://access.redhat.com/security/cve/CVE-2022-2196",
				"source": "CVE"
			}
		],
		"description": "DOCUMENTATION: A flaw was found in the KVM's Intel nested virtualization feature (nVMX). Since L1 and L2 shared branch prediction modes (guest-user and guest-kernel), KVM did not protect indirect branches in L1 from steering by a malicious agent in L2. This could allow a malicious nested guest to carry out Spectre v2 attacks against L1 due to a missing IBPB at VM-exit time. \n            STATEMENT: Red Hat currently provides the nested virtualization feature as a Technology Preview. Nested virtualization is therefore unsupported for production use. For more information please refer to https://access.redhat.com/solutions/21101 and https://access.redhat.com/support/offerings/techpreview.\n            MITIGATION: This vulnerability can be mitigated by disabling the nested virtualization feature:\n```\n# modprobe -r kvm_intel\n# modprobe kvm_intel nested=0\n```",
